                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "the estimation technique can be reapplied during development, and the estimate inputs are directly comparable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "A disadvantage is not explicitly stated in the context, but it can be inferred that this measure might be too general and not provide detailed insights into specific aspects of the system.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another size measure described by Lorenz and Kidd (1994) is counting the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in the use cases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lorenz and Kidd count the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in the use cases.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This measure is correlated with application size and number of test cases, making it useful for feeding estimation models for predicting project effort or duration and for helping the test team prepare test cases and allocate resources for future testing activities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They report that this measure is correlated with application size and number of test cases. For this reason, NSS is useful in at least two ways. As a size measure, it can feed an estimation model for predicting project effort or duration. As a test case estimate, it helps the test team prepare test cases and allocate resources for future testing activities.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
