[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Yes, it is appropriate to specify that the system should not do what it is not intended to do.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "successful, it is important that the requirements be of high quality; what is not specified usually is not built.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This is because requirements need to be correct, consistent, unambiguous, and complete, specifying required behavior and output for all possible inputs in all possible states under all possible constraints.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "1. Are the requirements correct? Both we and the customer should review the documented requirements, to ensure that they conform to our understanding of the requirements.\n2. Are the requirements consistent? That is, are there any conflicting requirements? For example, if one requirement states that a maximum of 10 users can be using the system at one time, and another requirement says that in a certain situation there may be 20 simultaneous users, the two requirements are said to be inconsistent.\n3. Are the requirements unambiguous? The requirements are ambiguous if multiple readers of the requirements can walk away with different but valid interpretations.\n4. Are the requirements complete? The set of requirements is complete if it specifies required behavior and output for all possible inputs in all possible states under all possible constraints.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An example would be a payroll system specifying what happens when an employee takes a leave without pay, gets a raise, or needs an advance, thereby implicitly specifying that the system should not process other unauthorized transactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, a payroll system should describe what happens when an employee takes a leave without pay, gets a raise, or needs an advance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Different consumers of software requirements include requirements analysts and their clients, designers, the test team, and the maintenance team.",
        "citations": [
