[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Robertsons' requirements definition template, available at http://www.systemsguild.com, is a comprehensive tool designed to assist software developers in eliciting and checking a set of requirements effectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A comprehensive requirements-definition template developed by James and Suzanne Robertson can be found at the Web site of the Atlantic Systems Guild: http:// www.systemsguild.com.This template is accompanied by a description of the Volere process model, which is a complete process for eliciting and checking a set of requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template is particularly helpful during the requirements elicitation and validation phases, where it guides developers in confirming that the proposed functions and constraints accurately reflect the customer's needs and intentions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We review the proposed functions and constraints, to confirm that they accurately reflect the customer's needs and intentions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To use the template for validating requirements, developers need to engage in activities such as reviewing the requirements for omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistency, assessing and documenting risks, discussing alternatives, and agreeing on approaches with stakeholders.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All requirements are checked again for omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistency. If any risk is involved in the development or in the actual functioning of the system, we can assess and document this risk, discuss and compare alternatives, and come to some agreement on the approaches to be used.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Developers must also plan for testing the system by determining how requirements will be revalidated as they evolve, who will provide test data, and which requirements will be tested in each phase.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can talk about testing the system: how the requirements will be revalidated as the requirements grow and change; who will provide test data to the test team; which requirements will be tested in which phases, if the system is to be developed in phases.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Effective use of the template requires developers to possess skills in communication and collaboration with customers and users, problem identification and resolution, and the ability to use validation techniques and tools that support checking consistency and completeness.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Whenever a problem is identified, the problem is documented, its cause is determined, and the requirements analysts are charged with the task of fixing the problem. Our choice of validation technique depends on the experience and preferences of the stakeholders and on the technique's appropriateness for the notations used in the requirements definition. Some notations have tool support for checking consistency and completeness.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template helps uncover errors and faults such as misunderstandings about function results, conflicting requirements between customers and users, unrealistic goals, omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistencies in the requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Validation may reveal that there is a great misunderstanding about the way in which a certain function will produce results. The customers may require data to be reported in miles, whereas the users want the data in kilometers. The customers may set a reliability or availability goal that developers deem impossible to meet. These conflicts need to be resolved before design can begin.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

