[
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Assessment of cohesion for each module:",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Module “InventorySearchByID” likely has high cohesion because it performs a single function: searching inventory records by ID and returning matching records.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our ideal is functional cohesion , where two conditions hold: all elements essential to a single function are contained in one module, and all of that module's elements are essential to the performance of that function. A functionally cohesive module performs only the function for which it is designed, and nothing else.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Module “ProcessPurchase” likely has low cohesion because it performs multiple unrelated functions: removing product from inventory, printing a receipt, and updating the log.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The worst degree of cohesion, coincidental , is found in a module whose parts are unrelated to one another. In this case, unrelated functions, processes, or data are combined in the same module for reasons of convenience or serendipity.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Module “FindSet” likely has low cohesion because it combines different phases: processing the request, determining matching items, and formatting the list for display, which are different functions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Sometimes a design is divided into modules that represent the different phases of execution: initialization, read input, compute, print output, and cleanup . The cohesion in these modules is temporal , in that a module's data and functions are related only because they are used at the same time in an execution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To say that a design review should be “egoless” means that the review process is not about placing blame on a particular developer when faults or failures are discovered, but rather about correcting the faults collaboratively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When a fault is discovered or a failure occurs, the egoless development team is concerned with correcting the fault, not with placing blame on a particular developer.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Egoless reviews are necessary because personal feelings can interfere with the testing and review process, making it difficult to objectively identify faults. An independent test team is often used to avoid conflicts between personal responsibility and the need to discover as many faults as possible.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Even when a system is developed with an egoless approach, we sometimes have difficulty removing our personal feelings from the testing process. Thus, we often use an independent test team to test a system. In this way, we avoid conflict between personal responsibility for faults and the need to discover as many faults as possible.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Steps that may help achieve egoless reviews include using an independent test team that participates in reviewing components throughout development, including requirements and design reviews, testing code components individually, and testing the system as it is integrated. This allows testing to proceed concurrently with coding and helps maintain objectivity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Furthermore, an independent test team can participate in reviewing the components throughout development. The team can be part of the requirements and design reviews, can test the code components individually, and can test the system as it is integrated and presented to the customers for acceptance. In this way, testing can proceed concurrently with coding; the test team can test components as they are completed and begin to piece them together while the programming staff continues to code other components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One example of a software system with an interface feature that can be disliked is an image-processing software that allows users to apply various operations to modify their pictures, such as rotation, color tinting, and cropping.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "(c) image-processing software that allows users to apply various operations to modify their pictures (e.g., rotation, color tinting, cropping)",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A common problem with such software interfaces is that some tools or functions may be difficult to find or use, leading to user frustration and inefficiency.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This problem could have been avoided during the design process by using user interface prototyping, which involves building a small version of the system with limited functionality to help users identify key requirements and provide feedback.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "User Interface Prototyping. Prototyping means building a small version of a system, usually with limited functionality, that can be used to help the user or customer identify the key requirements of a system",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Iterative prototyping, where prototypes are built, evaluated with user feedback, and refined, would help surface issues and assumptions about the interface early on, leading to a more user-friendly design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Often, the prototyping process is iterative: We build a prototype, evaluate it (with user and customer feedback), consider how changes might improve the product or design, and then build another prototype.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Since the user interface is, in a sense, a bridge between the application domain and the software development team, prototyping can bring to the surface issues and assumptions that may not have been clear using other approaches to requirements analysis.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A well-known source that deals with design patterns in more detail is the collection presented by Gamma et al. (1995).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The collection presented by Gamma et al. (1995) is a good place to start.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One of the patterns presented is the Template Method pattern, which aims to reduce the amount of duplicate code among subclasses.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "## Template Method Pattern The Template Method pattern aims to reduce the amount of duplicate code among subcla",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Design patterns codify design decisions and best practices for solving particular design problems according to design principles. They serve as templates for solutions that must be adapted for each use, improving a design's modularity by encapsulating particular types of design decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A design pattern codifies design decisions and best practices for solving a particular design problem according to design principles, some of which were identified earlier in this chapter. Design patterns are not the same as software libraries; they are not packaged solutions that can be used as is. Rather, they are templates for a solution that must be modified and adapted for each particular use. ... The main goal of design patterns is to improve a design's modularity. In fact, each pattern is designed to encapsulate a particular type of design decision.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Design patterns are useful when extra flexibility and modularity are needed, such as making future design changes easier or enabling a program to change its structure or behavior at runtime.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some design patterns structure a design to make future design changes easier to implement. Other patterns enable a program to change its structure or behavior at runtime.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, using design patterns can introduce complexity by adding extra classes, associations, and method calls, which may impact performance or ease of development. Therefore, they are best used when the benefits of flexibility outweigh these costs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because the patterns add extra classes, associations, and method calls, they sometimes can seem overly complicated. This complexity improves modularity, even at the expense of other quality attributes such as performance or ease of development. For this reason, the patterns are useful only in situations where the extra flexibility is worth the extra cost required to implement them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Therac-25 accidents highlight several important lessons for design in safety-critical systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe the machine, the accidents, and the software issues in great detail, and their article should be required reading for systems and software engineers who design and build safety-critical systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Key lessons learned include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Most computer-related accidents result from requirements faults, not from coding faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They point out that most computer-related accidents result from requirements faults, not from coding faults",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process, including early standards and evaluation of intermediate products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process. These practices should include standards that are set early and used to evaluate intermediate products.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Timing errors can be difficult to reproduce and can cause serious accidents.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe how the underlying cause of the problems was a timing error that was difficult to reproduce.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Safety analysis techniques such as failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA), fault-tree analysis, and detailed code inspections are crucial to identify hazards and recommend hardware and software changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Atomic Energy of Canada Limited (AECL) performed a safety analysis of the Therac25 system. AECL began with a failure modes and effects analysis to identify single failures leading to significant hazards. Then, to identify multiple failures and quantify the results, it performed a fault-tree analysis. Finally, it hired an outside consultant to perform detailed code inspections of the software functions related to the most serious hazards: electron-beam scanning, energy selection, beam shutoff, and dose calibration.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The AECL final report recommended 10 changes to the Therac-25 hardware, including interlocks to back up software control of energy selection and electron-beam scanning.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Object-Oriented characteristics of encapsulation and information hiding support reuse by providing flexibility in encapsulating design decisions and modifying and reusing designs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Both the separation of object instances from instance variables and of interfaces from class definitions give us considerable flexibility in encapsulating design decisions and in modifying and reusing designs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Encapsulation allows a composite class to manipulate its object-based attributes only through their interfaces, without knowing their implementations, which supports modularity and makes it easy to replace one class component with another as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An advantage of object composition is its support of modularity; the composite class knows nothing about the implementations of its object-based attributes and can manipulate these attributes only by using their interfaces. As such, we can easily replace one class component with another, as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Inheritance supports reuse by allowing new classes to be defined by extending or modifying existing classes, inheriting their data and function definitions, which reduces the need to redefine common features.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Alternatively, we can build new classes by extending or modifying definitions of existing classes. This kind of construction, called inheritance, defines a new class by directly reusing (and adding to) the definitions of an existing class.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In deciding whether to reuse a class in a new system, criteria include whether the class complies with the required interface, whether it performs the required function acceptably (e.g., failure-free if code), and whether the effort to understand and modify the component is less than the effort to write a new equivalent component.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An important issue in black-box reuse is our ability to verify that a reused module performs its required function in an acceptable way. If the component is code, we want to be sure it is failure-free; if it is a test set, we want to be sure it thoroughly exercises the function for which it is intended.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Clear-box reuse (sometimes called white-box reuse) is more common but still controversial, because the effort to understand and modify the component must be less than the effort to write a new equivalent component.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is useful to have separate phases for system and program design because program designers become deeply involved with the details of the code and may sometimes neglect the larger picture of how the system should work.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For similar reasons, it is useful for program designers to be different from system designers. Program designers become deeply involved with the details of the code, and they sometimes neglect the larger picture of how the system should work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Separating these roles allows for techniques such as walkthroughs, inspections, and reviews to bring the two types of designers together to double-check the design before coding, as well as to provide continuity in the development process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We will see in later chapters that techniques such as walkthroughs, inspections, and reviews can bring the two types of designers together to double-check the design before it goes on to be coded, as well as to provide continuity in the development process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important if two different terms are being used to refer to the same entity because this can lead to confusion and inconsistency in the use cases, making it harder to clearly understand and specify the system behavior.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Use cases are used to specify user views of essential system behavior. They model only system functionality that can be initiated by some actor in the environment.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each use case identifies pre-conditions and alternative behavior if the pre-conditions are not met, such as looking for a lost book; post-conditions, which summarize the effects of the use case; and a normal, error-free scenario comprising a sequence of steps performed by actors or by the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using different terms for the same entity can obscure the understanding of actors and system interactions, which are central to use cases, and can cause errors in specifying scenarios, pre-conditions, and post-conditions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Use cases model only system functionality that can be initiated by some actor in the environment.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each use case encompasses several possible scenarios, some successful and some not, but all related to some usage of the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using inheritance to create separate subclasses for each service, such as purchasing books and rebinding books, from a general 'sale item' class offers several benefits.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If we define Bulk Sale as an extension of our regular Sale class, as in Figure 6.12, then we need to provide only the definitions that distinguish Bulk Sale from its parent class, Sale.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The likely benefits of using inheritance in this case include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Code reuse by inheriting common attributes and methods from the general sale item class, reducing duplication.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Any Bulk Sale object will comprise attributes and methods defined in the parent Sale class together with those defined in the Bulk Sale class.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Polymorphism, allowing code to interact with sale items through a common interface while the specific behavior depends on the subclass type (e.g., purchase or rebinding).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Objects of different types may react to the same message by producing type-specific responses. Designers and programmers need not know the exact types of the objects that the polymorphic code is manipulating.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Simplified maintenance and extension, since new sale item types can be added by creating new subclasses without modifying existing code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Inheritance, object composition, and polymorphism are important features of an OO design that make the resulting system more useful in many ways.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are arguments against using inheritance in this case, and factors that could influence the decision include:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Possible arguments against using inheritance and factors influencing the decision are",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Inheritance can lead to a rigid class hierarchy that may be difficult to change if the services evolve or new services are added that do not fit well into the existing hierarchy.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A key design decision is determining how best to structure and relate complex objects. In an OO system, there are two main techniques for constructing large objects: inheritance and composition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "If the services share little in common beyond being sale items, inheritance might force inappropriate or unnecessary attributes or methods into subclasses.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Object composition might be a better alternative if the services are better modeled as combinations of simpler objects rather than as a strict hierarchy.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Inheritance vs. Object Composition A key design decision is determining how best to structure and relate complex objects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Design complexity, runtime performance, and ease of maintenance should be evaluated when deciding between inheritance and composition.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Although wrapper classes ease the task of adding operations to composite classes, they can complicate the design and degrade runtime performance. Thus, deciding whether to adhere to the Law of Demeter involves evaluating trade-offs among design complexity, development time, runtime performance, fault avoidance, and ease of maintenance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
