[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The relationship between design and implementation is critical because the design serves as a guide to the function or purpose of each component, while the implementation is the actual coding of that design into a working system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Programming involves a great deal of creativity. Remember that the design is a guide to the function or purpose of each component, but the programmer has great flexibility in implementing the design as code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important to match the implementation to the design to ensure that the modularity, low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces specified in the design are carried forward into the code. This correspondence allows the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures to be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The most critical standard is the need for a direct correspondence between the program design components and the program code components. The entire design process is of little value if the design's modularity is not carried forward into the code. Design characteristics, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should also be program characteristics, so that the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Maintaining this correspondence is essential because the system's general purpose may remain the same over its lifetime, but its nature may change due to enhancements and modifications. Changes are first made to the high-level design and then traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified. Without this link, testing, maintenance, and configuration management become impossible.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Remember that the system's general purpose is likely to remain the same throughout the software's lifetime, but its nature may change over time as customers identify enhancements and modifications. ... These changes are made first to the high-level design and then are traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified. Thus, the correspondence between design and code is essential. In later chapters, we will see that testing, maintenance, and configuration management are impossible without the links established by these standards.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To keep the design and implementation consistent, one should ensure that the design's modularity and characteristics are reflected in the code, use clear documentation and standards, and maintain traceability between design components and code components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The most critical standard is the need for a direct correspondence between the program design components and the program code components. ... Design characteristics, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should also be program characteristics, so that the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The kind of reuse where you use components originally developed for other projects is called consumer reuse.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are two kinds of reuse: producer reuse, where we are creating components designed to be reused in subsequent applications, and consumer reuse, where we are using components that were originally developed for other projects (Barnes and Bollinger 1991).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Problems encountered in reuse can include conflicts in reuse goals between different management levels, difficulties in measuring reuse success, and social, cultural, and legal issues that make reuse seem radical and threatening to developers accustomed to writing software from scratch.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Reuse goals can conflict, and management must resolve conflicts early and clearly. For example, as shown in Figure 12.7, a division manager's reuse goal may conflict with a project manager's goal, so no reuse ever gets done.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, reuse often seems radical and threatening to developers who are accustomed to writing software from scratch. It is clear that many social, cultural, and legal issues are involved in reuse, as well as technical ones.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To resolve these problems, organizations must have clear management commitment, select appropriate target domains, systematically develop reusable modules based on domain analysis, and invest several years of continuous effort in reuse.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They found that their critical success factors were (Isoda 1992) - senior management commitment - selecting appropriate target domains - systematic development of reusable modules based on domain analysis - investing several years of continuous effort in reuse.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, reuse goals should be measurable to determine if they have been met, and conflicts in goals must be resolved early and clearly by management.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Reuse goals should be measurable, so that we can tell if we have met them. Reuse goals can conflict, and management must resolve conflicts early and clearly.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A guideline that may help is to decide at what organizational level key questions about reuse are asked and answered, such as who pays for reuse, who owns the reusable components, and who builds and maintains them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Every organization must decide at what level certain key questions are asked and answered. For example: Who pays for reuse? ... And who owns the reusable components? ... Who builds the components? Another level must be responsible for the construction, population, and support of reuse libraries, as well as the measurement data generated by them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Also, involving a reuse council or team to select candidate components for reuse based on features common to multiple projects and monitoring reuse levels can improve reuse success.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Council created an inventory of components and formed a matrix with the features of all past and planned projects. Then, each feature was rated in terms of whether it had been implemented and was still needed, had been implemented but was no longer needed, or had not been implemented but was still needed. Those features that were needed and were common to more than one project were targeted for reuse.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When writing code in a team environment, it is crucial to have coding standards and procedures to ensure clarity, consistency, and maintainability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Even when writing the code itself, many people are usually involved, and a great deal of cooperation and coordination is required. Thus, it is very important for others to be able to understand not only what you have written, but also why you have written it and how it fits in with their work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Below is a set of coding standards for the Python programming language, based on the guidelines from the chapter:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Coding Standards for Python:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Follow a consistent style for indentation and formatting, such as using 4 spaces per indentation level.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many companies insist that their code conform to style, format, and content standards, so that the code and associated documentation are clear to everyone who reads them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use meaningful variable and function names that clearly describe their purpose.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Standards and procedures can help you to organize your thoughts and avoid mistakes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Document your code thoroughly with comments explaining what the code does, why certain decisions were made, and how it fits into the larger system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some of the procedures involve methods of documenting your code so that it is clear and easy to follow. Such documentation allows you to leave and return to your work without losing track of what you had been doing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Structure your code to maintain correspondence between design components and code components, making it easier to implement design changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By structuring code according to standards, you maintain the correspondence between design components and code components. Consequently, changes in design are easy to implement in the code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use version control systems to manage changes and facilitate collaboration among team members.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Adhere to common development tools and languages agreed upon by the team to ensure compatibility and ease of communication.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Nearly all of Microsoft's teams work at a single physical site, using common development languages (usually C and C++), common coding styles, and standard development tools. These standards help teams to communicate, to discuss the pros and cons of different design alternatives, and to resolve problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These standards are included to ensure that code is understandable and maintainable by others, to facilitate teamwork and coordination, and to reduce errors when implementing changes or integrating with other components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Standardized documentation also helps in locating faults and making changes, because it clarifies which sections of your program perform which functions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Once your code is complete, others are likely to use it in a variety of ways. ... it is essential that you organize, format, and document your code to make it easy for others to understand what it does and how it works.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To examine faults from code you have written, first identify the type of fault according to the IBM Orthogonal Defect Classification scheme presented in Table 8.1.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "TABLE 8.1, 1 = IBMOrthogonal Defect Classification. FaultType, 1 = Meaning. Function, 1 = Fault that affects capability, end-user interfaces, product interfaces, interface with hardware architecture, or global data structure. Interface, 1 = Fault in interacting with other components or drivers via calls, macros, control blocks, or parameter lists. Checking, 1 = Fault in program logic that fails to validate data and values properly before they are used. Assignment, 1 = Fault in data structure or code block initialization. Timing/serialization, 1 = Fault that involves timing of shared and real-time resources. Build/package/merge, 1 = Fault that occurs because of problems in repositories,management changes, or version control. Documentation, 1 = Fault that affects publications and maintenance notes. Algorithm, 1 = Fault involving efficiency or correctness of algorithm or data structure but not design",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Use the orthogonal defect classification approach, which requires that each fault belongs to exactly one category to ensure unambiguous classification. This helps in meaningful summary and consistent classification by different developers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the key features of orthogonal defect classification is its orthogonality. That is, a classification scheme is orthogonal if any item being classified belongs to exactly one category. In other words, we want to track the faults in our system in an unambiguous way, so that the summary information about the number of faults in each class is meaningful. We lose the meaning of the measurements if a fault might belong to more than one class. In the same way, the fault classification must be clear, so that any two developers are likely to classify a particular fault in the same way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For each fault, also determine whether it is a fault of omission (something missing, e.g., a variable not initialized) or a fault of commission (something incorrect, e.g., variable initialized to the wrong value).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When using the classification, the developers identify not only the type of fault, but also whether it is a fault of omission or commission. A fault of omission is one that results when some key aspect of the code is missing; for example, a fault may occur when a variable is not initialized. A fault of commission is one that is incorrect; for example, the variable is initialized to the wrong value.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Alternatively, you may use Hewlett-Packard's fault classification scheme, which involves selecting three descriptors for each fault: the origin of the fault (where it was injected), the type of fault, and the mode (whether information was missing, unclear, wrong, changed, or could be done a better way).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The developers use this model by selecting three descriptors for each fault found: the origin of the fault (i.e., where the fault was injected in a product), the type of fault, and the mode (i.e., whether information was missing, unclear, wrong, changed, or could be done a better way).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Difficulties in classifying faults may include ambiguity in fault categorization if a fault seems to belong to more than one category, or if the fault description is unclear. Ensuring orthogonality and clarity in classification helps reduce these difficulties.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We lose the meaning of the measurements if a fault might belong to more than one class. In the same way, the fault classification must be clear, so that any two developers are likely to classify a particular fault in the same way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

