[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing focuses on testing individual components to ensure that the code implements the design properly, meaning that programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing involves combining individual components into a working system and testing them together to ensure that the components work correctly when integrated.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system. This integration is planned and coordinated so that when a failure occurs, we have some idea of what caused it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The goal of unit testing is to verify that each component functions correctly in isolation according to its design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The goal of integration testing is to ensure that the combined components work together correctly as a system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing should occur when individual components are developed, allowing complete control over the testing process, including creating test data and designing test cases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When you unit test your components, you have complete control over the testing process. You create your own test data, design your own test cases, and run the tests yourself.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing should be planned and coordinated, often involving collaboration with the test or development team, and it occurs after unit testing when components are combined.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When you integrate components, you sometimes work by yourself, but often you collaborate with some of the test or development team.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This integration is planned and coordinated so that when a failure occurs, we have some idea of what caused it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Object-oriented testing differs from traditional testing in several key ways related to the nature of objects and their interactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Aspects of object orientation that affect testing include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways. First, she notes which aspects of object orientation make testing easier and which make it harder.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Objects tend to be small, pushing complexity toward interfaces among components, making unit testing easier but integration testing more extensive.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "objects tend to be small, and the complexity that might ordinarily reside in the component is often pushed instead toward the interfaces among components. This difference means that unit testing is less difficult, but integration testing must be much more extensive.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Encapsulation isolates components, which requires more extensive integration testing despite being a positive design attribute.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "encapsulation is often considered a positive attribute of object-oriented design, but it also requires more extensive integration testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Inheritance necessitates additional testing if inherited functions are redefined, have specific behavior in derived classes, or need consistency with other functions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, inheritance introduces the need for more testing. An inherited function needs additional testing if it is redefined, it has a specific behavior in a derived class, other functions in that class are supposed to be consistent",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Traditional testing approaches focus on functions and procedural code, whereas object-oriented testing must consider object states, inheritance, and interactions among objects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The traditional testing approaches apply well to functions, but many approaches do not take into account the object states needed to test classes.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For procedural languages, we can use a set of test data to test a system; then, when a change is made to the system, we can test that the change is correct and use the existing test data to verify that the additional, remaining functionality is still the same. But Perry and Kaiser (1990) show that the situation is different for object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In object-oriented testing, when a subclass overrides an inherited method, the overriding subclass must be retested, often with different test data, unlike in traditional testing where existing test data can often be reused.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When a subclass replaces an inherited method with a locally defined method with the same name, the overriding subclass must be retested, and probably with a different set of test data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Object-oriented testing requires special treatment in requirements analysis and validation, test case generation, source code analysis, and coverage analysis due to the nature of objects and methods.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "requirements analysis and validation, test case generation, source code analysis, and coverage analysis require special treatment.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Specific challenges in object-oriented testing tools and metrics include:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "requirements are likely to be expressed in the requirements document, but there are few tools to support validation of requirements expressed as objects and methods. Likewise, most tools that assist in test case generation are not prepared to handle a model expressed in objects and methods. Most source code measurements are defined for procedural code, not for objects and methods. Traditional metrics such as cyclomatic numbers are of little use when assessing the size and complexity of object-oriented systems. Because it is the interaction of objects that is the source of complexity, code coverage measurements and tools are of less value in object-oriented testing than in traditional testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Statement testing requires that every statement in the component is executed at least once in some test.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Statement testing: Every statement in the component is executed at least once in some test.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "All-uses testing requires that the test set includes at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All-uses testing: The test set includes at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, consider a piece of code with statements numbered 1 through 7. Statement testing requires test cases that execute statements 1 through 7 at least once.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Statement testing requires test cases that execute statements 1 through 7.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To satisfy statement testing, one test case that executes all statements once is sufficient.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By choosing X larger than K that produces a positive RESULT, we can execute statements in order, so one test case suffices.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For all-uses testing, test cases must include at least one path from every definition to every use of that definition, which generally requires more test cases than statement testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All-uses testing: The test set includes at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding the strength of testing strategies, all-uses testing is stronger than statement testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Beizer (1990) describes the relative strengths of these test strategies, as shown in Figure 8.6. For example, testing all paths is stronger than testing all paths from definition to use.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In general, the stronger the strategy, the more test cases are involved.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In general, the stronger the strategy, the more test cases are involved; we must always consider the trade-off between the resources available for testing and the thoroughness of the strategy we choose.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, all-uses testing requires more test cases than statement testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In our example, statement testing requires fewer test cases than branch testing, which in turn requires fewer cases than path testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "System testing differs from unit and integration testing in its objective and scope.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.In system testing, we have a very different objective: to ensure that the system does what the customer wants it to do.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing focuses on testing individual components in isolation to verify that each component functions properly with expected inputs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Unit testing is done in a controlled environment whenever possible, so that the test team can feed a predetermined set of data to the component being tested and observe what output actions and data are produced.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing verifies that the interfaces among components are defined and handled properly and that the system components work together as described in the system and program design specifications.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Integration testing is the process of verifying that the system components work together as described in the system and program design specifications.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "System testing evaluates the entire integrated system to ensure it performs the functions described by the requirements specification and meets the customer's expectations.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A function test evaluates the system to determine if the functions described by the requirements specification are actually performed by the integrated system. The result is a functioning system.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The function test compares the system being built with the functions described in the developer's requirements specification.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Function testing compares the system being built with the functions described in the developer's requirements specification to ensure the system functions according to the design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The function test compares the system being built with the functions described in the developer's requirements specification.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Performance testing compares the system with the remainder of the software and hardware requirements to confirm that the system functions according to the developers' understanding of the system description.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Then, a performance test compares the system with the remainder of these software and hardware requirements. When the performance test is complete, we developers are certain that the system functions according to our understanding of the system description.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Acceptance testing is performed jointly with the customer to check the system against the customer's requirements description, ensuring the system works according to customer expectations.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The next step is conferring with the customer to make certain that the system works according to customer expectations. We join the customer to perform an acceptance test, where the system is checked against the customer's requirements description.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Installation testing involves installing the system at user sites and configuring it to the user environment to verify that the system works properly under actual site conditions, especially if acceptance testing was not performed on-site.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The final round of testing involves installing the system at user sites. If acceptance testing has been performed on-site, installation testing may not be needed. However, if the acceptance testing conditions were not the same as the actual site conditions, additional testing is necessary. To begin installation testing, we configure the system to the user environment.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Installation testing focuses on two main aspects:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The tests focus on two things: completeness of the installed system and verification of any functional or nonfunctional characteristics that may be affected by site conditions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Completeness of the installed system, ensuring all necessary files and devices are present.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The test cases assure the customer that the system is complete and that all necessary files and devices are present.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Verification of any functional or nonfunctional characteristics that may be affected by site conditions, such as environmental factors.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The tests focus on ... verification of any functional or nonfunctional characteristics that may be affected by site conditions. For example, a system designed to work aboard a ship must be tested to demonstrate that it is not affected by the severe weather or the ship's motion.",
