[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The principles of Cleanroom software development include separation of the development and test teams, reliance on peer review instead of unit testing, use of informal state machines and functions to define the system design, and statistical testing based on operational scenarios.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- separation of the development and test teams\n- reliance on peer review instead of unit testing\n- use of informal state machines and functions to define the system design\n- statistical testing based on operational scenarios",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom shifts effort from coding to design, with developers spending about half their time writing code and half reading it, compared to traditional developers who spend 85% of their time writing code and 15% reading it. This approach increases productivity by 50% and decreases rework.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Basili and Green (1994) found that 6% of project effort shifted from coding to design when cleanroom was used. Also, whereas traditional developers spent 85% of their time writing code and 15% reading it, the cleanroom team spent about half its time on each activity. Productivity increased by 50% and the amount of rework decreased.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom differs from conventional testing in that it relies on statistical testing based on operational scenarios rather than unit testing, and emphasizes peer review and formal design methods such as box structures instead of traditional testing methods.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- reliance on peer review instead of unit testing\n- statistical testing based on operational scenarios",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "they combined statistical testing with functional testing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "they emphasized box structures instead of state machines.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, Cleanroom has some drawbacks: participants may dislike using design abstractions and box structures, feel uncomfortable with being unable to compile their code, and have difficulty coordinating developers and testers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Cleanroom participants did not like using design abstractions and box structures, were uncomfortable with being unable to compile their code, and had difficulty coordinating developers and testers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, conventional testing often involves unit testing, developers controlling testing, and may lack formal methods training or use of statistical testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The 'control' group of testers had no training or experience in proper testing methods.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Basili and Green (1994) acknowledged the traditional SEL reliance on testing. They felt it too risky to remove testing completely from the developers' control.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

