        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For projects using English requirements, measurements should include the number of requirements and the number of changes to requirements, as these indicate the size of the system and the stability or uncertainty in understanding what the system should do.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The number of requirements in the requirements definition and specification can give us a sense of how large the developed system is likely to be. ... Similarly, we can measure the number of changes to requirements. A large number of changes indicates some instability or uncertainty in our understanding of what the system should do or how it should behave, and suggests that we should take actions to try to lower the rate of changes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For the trial project using Z, the same types of measurements should be collected to compare the size, stability, and quality of requirements against the English-language process. Additionally, tracking changes and the impact of changes throughout development is important to assess whether Z improves requirements stability and clarity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The tracking of changes also can continue throughout development; as the system requirements change, the impact of the changes can be assessed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Collecting these measurements allows the organization to assess whether the formal language Z leads to better-defined, more stable requirements and whether it improves the overall requirements process compared to the informal English-language approach.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Measurements usually focus on three areas: product, process, and resources (Fenton and Pfleeger 1997).",
                "img_id": null
