[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Vic Basili's 1997 paper on software reading describes a series of studies that each contributed knowledge about the use of software reading technology in particular environments, using different types of studies for different goals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a 1997 paper, Vic Basili describes a series of studies of a particular kind of software technology, called software reading. (V. Basili (1997). “Evolving and packaging reading techniques.” Journal of Systems and Software, 38: 3 - 12.) Each study in the series contributed some knowledge about the use of this technology in a particular environment. A number of different types of studies were used: Some studies looked at whether or not the technology was feasible in the environment, other studies tested very specific hypotheses about the technology, and still other studies examined the use of the technology in detail.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For the goal of determining whether the technology is feasible in the environment, I would recommend feasibility studies that assess the practicality and initial applicability of software reading in the organization's context.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For testing very specific hypotheses about the technology, I would recommend controlled experiments or hypothesis-driven studies that isolate variables and measure the effects of software reading techniques under defined conditions.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For examining the use of the technology in detail, I would recommend observational studies, case studies, or detailed usage analyses that provide in-depth understanding of how software reading is applied and its impact in real-world settings.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A recommended series of studies for the organization interested in software reading (Z) would be:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "First, conduct feasibility studies to determine if software reading can be effectively introduced and used in the organization's environment",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Next, perform controlled experiments to test specific hypotheses about the benefits or limitations of software reading techniques in the organization's context",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Finally, carry out detailed observational or case studies to analyze how software reading is actually used, its challenges, and its outcomes in practice within the organization",
        "citations": []
    }
]

