    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Empirical studies in software engineering that involve human subjects differ significantly from those that do not, primarily due to the need to assess human behavior, usability, and the practical application of development techniques. For example, a study investigating the effectiveness of a new software design method must consider who uses the method, how they use it, and the context in which it is applied. This contrasts with studies of algorithms or technologies that focus solely on performance metrics like speed or accuracy without human interaction.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, if we are investigating the effect of a design method on the quality of the resulting software, but we have no control over who is using which design method, then we do a case study to document the results. Experiments are done only when we can manipulate behavior directly, precisely, and systematically.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Studies involving human subjects require careful control of variables related to human behavior and context, which can be challenging. For instance, an experiment might control who uses a particular method and when, allowing for systematic comparison. In contrast, studies without human subjects, such as those comparing algorithms, can focus on measurable outputs under controlled conditions without accounting for human factors. This difference affects the generalizability and applicability of the results, as experiments with human subjects often need to consider variability in human performance and environmental factors.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Experiments are done only when we can manipulate behavior directly, precisely, and systematically. Thus, if we can control who uses the cleanroom method, who uses SSADM, and when and where they are used, then we can perform an experiment.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One key motivator for using a formal experiment rather than a case study or survey is that the results of an experiment are usually more generalizable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two notable approaches to process improvement in software engineering are the Cleanroom approach and the Return on Investment (ROI) approach.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "## Cleanroom\n\nNASA's Software Engineering Laboratory evaluated and improved processes for several decades. Basili and Green (1994) described how the SEL introduced new technology, assessed its effects, and took advantage of those tools and techniques that offered significant improvement.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "## Return on Investment\n\nIn an ongoing attempt to improve software development, we select from among recommended methods and tools. Usually, limited resources constrain our choice; we cannot do everything, so we search for criteria for choosing the one(s) most likely to help us reach our goal.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Cleanroom approach, as implemented by NASA's Software Engineering Laboratory (SEL), involves introducing new technology cautiously, assessing its effects through formal, controlled experiments or case studies, and then applying successful techniques in real-world environments. This approach emphasizes risk management by initially applying new tools outside normal project environments to avoid threatening project goals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "NASA's Software Engineering Laboratory evaluated and improved processes for several decades. Basili and Green (1994) described how the SEL introduced new technology, assessed its effects, and took advantage of those tools and techniques that offered significant improvement. The SEL took into account the risks involved in using a new technology; where appropriate, the technique or tool was applied outside of the normal project environment, where its use would not threaten project goals.\n\nThese offline studies were usually performed as formal, controlled experiments or case studies.The SEL usually began with a small experiment, where the size permitted the variables to be controlled easily.Then, when experimental results looked promising, an industrial-strength case study verified that the small-scale results worked in real-world environments.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Cleanroom approach has been applied extensively at NASA, demonstrating its effectiveness in improving software processes and products. The approach requires organizational support for controlled experimentation, risk management, and knowledge packaging to disseminate successful practices.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "NASA's Software Engineering Laboratory evaluated and improved processes for several decades. Basili and Green (1994) described how the SEL introduced new technology, assessed its effects, and took advantage of those tools and techniques that offered significant improvement.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Once the SEL was satisfied that a new technique would be good for NASA's developers and maintainers, it packaged the lessons learned so that others could understand and use the technology.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the Return on Investment (ROI) approach focuses on selecting process improvement methods and tools based on their expected financial and operational benefits. It emphasizes evaluating technology investments using multiple criteria, including customer satisfaction, operational capabilities, financial returns, and market leadership.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In an ongoing attempt to improve software development, we select from among recommended methods and tools. Usually, limited resources constrain our choice; we cannot do everything, so we search for criteria for choosing the one(s) most likely to help us reach our goal.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Respected business publications often address the problem of technology investment. For example, an often-cited article suggests that any evaluation of an existing or proposed investment in technology be reported in several ways at once to form a 'balanced scorecard': from a customer view (i.e., customer satisfaction), an operational view (i.e., core competencies), a financial view (i.e., return on investment, share price), and an improvement view (i.e., market leadership and added value) (Kaplan and Norton 1992).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ROI approach has been applied in various industries, such as banking, where Chase Manhattan Bank demonstrated returns on investment from software process improvement. This approach requires organizational support for financial analysis, balanced evaluation metrics, and prioritization of improvement initiatives based on expected returns.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, Sidebar 12.8 describes some of the returns on investment at Chase Manhattan Bank.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Comparing the two approaches, Cleanroom is more focused on controlled experimentation and risk-managed adoption of new technologies, suitable for organizations with the capacity to conduct formal studies and manage technical risks. The ROI approach is broader, emphasizing financial and operational justification for process improvement investments, making it suitable for organizations needing to prioritize limited resources and demonstrate business value.",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In summary, organizations considering investing in process improvement should evaluate their capacity for controlled experimentation and risk management (favoring Cleanroom) versus their need for financial justification and balanced performance metrics (favoring ROI). Both approaches have demonstrated effectiveness in their respective contexts and require organizational commitment to support their methodologies.",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The recognition-primed decision model suggests that individuals make decisions by referring to a mental repository of past examples and comparing the current situation to these to find a close enough match, then mentally simulating the outcome before acting.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Klein has suggested a 'recognition-primed decision model,' as shown in Figure 14.6, to describe how we really make decisions. He points out that we tend to keep a repository of examples in our heads, and we draw on these situations when we are confronted with a choice. We mentally refer to a past situation and compare the current one to see if it is similar. Rather than comparing all the options, we grab one that is 'close,' and we go through a process in our heads to justify to ourselves that it is 'close enough' to be used as a basis for the current decision. At the same time, we use mental simulation to determine if the actions we propose to take will really work in this situation; when we don't think they will, then we back up, choose a different scenario, and perform the mental simulation again. Eventually, when we are satisfied that we have made the right choice, we act."
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Applying this model directly to an organization by creating an organizational 'experience base' that describes the past work of all employees and can be searched for answers to new problems is an ongoing effort.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are complications that must be overcome before such systems could be effective.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Some complications include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
